{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the handoff between request-construction and API-client modules (MOCK-MISS), not OS/network-dependent. A wired in-process test can assert the outbound payload contains every taxonomy label. Rejected higher levels because behavior text is about request shape ('request sent ... includes ... labels'), not real HTTP behavior or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier + request builder + fake API client; invoke classify() with a taxonomy fixture; assert captured outbound request contains the full label set exactly once and no omissions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic normalization/membership logic on one response value; no real infra, no multi-module boundary required, no LLM quality dependency. Rejected Integration because behavior text focuses on mapping an out-of-taxonomy label to 'unknown', which can be exercised in a single function boundary.","test_description":"Call normalization/decision function with taxonomy [legal, technical, financial, other] and raw label 'sports'; assert final label is 'unknown'.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.84,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Pure determinism property of normalization step; no I/O, no cross-module dependency needed to expose failure. Rejected higher levels because behavior explicitly scopes to 'normalization step' and 'identical raw API responses'.","test_description":"Run normalization multiple times with the same raw response fixture (including casing/whitespace variants already resolved in fixture) and assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live AI outputs ('repeated live API calls') and stability of model/provider decisions, which a stub cannot validate (LLM-DEP, MOCK-HIDE). Not Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Execute N real classification calls for the same document+taxonomy against the provider; record raw provider outputs and final labels; assert label stays stable when raw provider response is unchanged, and only label changes when provider response changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at module handoff (budget calculator/tokenizer + request constructor + dispatcher gate). In-process wiring with fake dispatcher catches whether over-budget requests are truncated/rejected before send. Rejected System because behavior text says 'before dispatch', so real network/OS is not required.","test_description":"Wire classifier with real budget policy + tokenizer module and fake dispatch client; feed over-budget document; assert policy action (truncate or reject) occurs and dispatch receives only compliant payload or no request.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Requires real provider token accounting from an actual AI API call; mocks can mask provider-side counting differences (MOCK-HIDE). Per LLM-DEP rule, execution through real AI/ML API defaults to Agentic even with deterministic assertions. Rejected Workflow because this is one model call, not multiple agentic stages.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real provider with production request template; capture provider-reported usage fields; assert total tokens <= configured budget across repeated runs and flag drift.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.01,"System":0.24,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core risk is retry orchestration across client wrapper, backoff policy, and caller contract; can be reproduced with a deterministic in-process stub returning rate-limit then success. Rejected System because behavior text is about control flow ('waits and retries') and does not require real network/OS semantics to expose the bug; rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model output content.","test_description":"Use stub API client sequence: rate-limit error (e.g., 429/Retry-After) then success; run classifier with fake clock/backoff; assert it waits per policy, r